{{Frame |Name gloss=Equality |Comments=Entered per the request after the April 2014 site visit. It is based on the 7 concepts submitted by us to IARPA in January 2014. The other 6 are Freedom, Equality, Democratic_institutions, Representation_and_decision-making, Organization_of_power,
Equality comes down to all members of a group or society having access to the same resources, without some members being valued less than others (Plato: ‘Friends have all things in common.’). In an equal society, citizens receive equal treatment in the eyes of the law. The parameters according to which equality is determined may vary. The venue in which citizens are treated equally are varied as well: they may have an equal right to vote (universal suffrage); equal right to opportunity (education, medical care). Equality is linked to freedom. Democratic institutions are numerous formal and informal conventional practices, laws, rules, and norms that are crucial for democratic laws and principles (along with the equality and freedom associated with democracy) to be practiced. Representation and decision-making are amongst the valued institutions of a recognized democracy, in addition to free economic institutions (including capitalism), political institutions, and social institutions.
